WEBVTT

00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:07.580
I would like to tell you all a story about how I

00:00:07.610 --> 00:00:12.410
ended up supporting the game dev industry on blue sky and the

00:00:12.410 --> 00:00:15.480
atmosphere, accidentally.

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:18.290
But first, an introduction.

00:00:18.290 --> 00:00:20.220
My name is Trezzy.

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:22.620
I've lived many lives.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:25.310
I've been a professional musician, an indie filmmaker, I

00:00:25.310 --> 00:00:28.560
've been a graphic designer, a stunt actor, but most

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:32.050
importantly, I've been a software engineer for more than two

00:00:32.050 --> 00:00:35.520
decades and I've been working in and around the games industry

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:36.600
for many years.

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:39.780
I'm also the founder of Burb House Games.

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:45.200
It's a game studio focused on building games using web technologies

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:45.590
.

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:50.620
I'm also the curator of the game dev feeds on blue

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:53.770
sky, the operator of the games industry labeler, also

00:00:53.770 --> 00:00:56.580
on blue sky, the author of happy view and debuff

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:58.640
and the steward of the Penaract, the founder

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:01.710
of cartridge, but I might be maybe getting a little bit

00:01:01.710 --> 00:01:04.310
ahead of myself here, so we'll we'll get into

00:01:04.330 --> 00:01:06.200
all of it.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:11.780
I want to preface this story by saying that I did

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:15.480
not start this journey that I'm about to describe with some

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:16.470
master plan.

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:18.830
I didn't sit down and say I'm going to save

00:01:18.830 --> 00:01:20.020
video games.

00:01:20.020 --> 00:01:24.170
I joined blue sky because I was mad at Twitter and so

00:01:24.170 --> 00:01:27.720
I started building because that's just sort of what I do

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:29.800
and once the ball was rolling there wasn't a whole lot

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:30.620
of stopping it.

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:33.190
So I'm going to walk you all through how I got

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:35.680
to where I am today with all the things that I've

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.170
built and I'm hopeful that you know with that discussion I

00:01:40.170 --> 00:01:44.530
can help others get started on some new projects, maybe find

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:48.650
direction on things that they've already begun, but most importantly

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:50.730
by the end of this thing we're going to try and

00:01:50.730 --> 00:01:54.690
distill a blueprint that you and other builders can use to make

00:01:54.690 --> 00:01:58.940
the atmosphere work for whatever industry you care about.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:02.570
To kick things off let me tell you about the game dev

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:03.270
feeds.

00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:08.260
When blue sky launched custom feeds I was stoked.

00:02:08.260 --> 00:02:12.440
Not only were we getting algorithmic choice but we had community

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:15.450
control over it and that was such a powerful idea.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:17.060
I was hooked.

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:21.540
I love video games and the game development community so I thought

00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:24.770
it sure would be cool to gather all of that content in

00:02:24.770 --> 00:02:27.570
a way that has never happened on Twitter.

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:29.560
So I built the game dev feeds.

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:32.510
There's the core of the game dev feed itself, which

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:34.770
is sort of the core of the community.

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:38.040
It acts as a town hall for our our little band.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:39.780
There's also game news.

00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:41.460
We've got jobs and careers.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:44.860
I also have the screenshot Saturday and Wishlist Wednesday feeds which

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:48.990
are both manifest versions of hashtag trends that game devs used

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:51.840
to use on on Twitter to share their games outside of the

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:53.040
developer community.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:56.900
At first these were nice little community tools.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:02:59.400
There were, you know, tens of people using them.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:01.140
I was very happy with that.

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:05.340
And then there were hundreds and then suddenly there were thousands of

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:09.820
feeds blew up and today I have around 32,000 daily

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:12.160
active users across the feeds.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:14.760
It's probably a drop in the bucket for Indra's

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:18.230
news feeds but for a much smaller community like game devs

00:03:18.230 --> 00:03:19.620
it's it's pretty exciting.

00:03:19.620 --> 00:03:22.740
So I hadn't planned for it but the community that had

00:03:22.740 --> 00:03:26.860
been gathering slowly suddenly they decided that blue sky and specifically the

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:29.520
feeds that I've been building made for a pretty good place

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:30.460
to be.

00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:34.410
Shout out by the way to great social who hosts all of

00:03:34.410 --> 00:03:37.250
my feeds they've provided me with the tools that enable the

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:39.380
feeds to thrive the way they do today.

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:42.130
If it wasn't for Devon reaching out about a year

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.900
ago I don't know if I'd be up here speaking

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:45.180
.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:47.800
A bit of time passed.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:52.770
Many alfs were exchanged and then blue sky launched labelers

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:52.960
.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.980
I thought, as I was seeing what other people were doing

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:58.510
with them, what if I could build a labeler that

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:02.500
helps people in the game dev industry find other professionals and track

00:04:02.510 --> 00:04:03.790
them throughout their timelines.

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:08.020
Developers, studios, publishers, journalists, media creators.

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:11.750
It seemed like a fun little project.

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:12.930
So I built it.

00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:15.060
I set up my own Ozone instance.

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:18.150
I was manually reviewing every request.

00:04:18.150 --> 00:04:19.020
It blew up.

00:04:19.020 --> 00:04:22.950
I was completely underwater with thousands of labeling requests coming through.

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:24.820
But the community found it really useful.

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:30.500
It helped them define and understand professional relationships and trust relationships across

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:31.620
blue sky.

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:36.810
Today, the labeler has over 6,000 game developers

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:41.690
, 450 studios, nearly 500 content creators in the games space

00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:47.450
, 700 games business folks, more than 150 games journalists.

00:04:47.450 --> 00:04:50.180
In total, like we said earlier, I applied more than

00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:55.140
9,000 labels to games industry professionals and businesses.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:58.420
The games industry, you know, it's continued to show

00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:01.310
up on the atmosphere in a way that I really never expected

00:05:01.310 --> 00:05:01.540
.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:03.860
And I didn't know it at the time.

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:07.270
But working on the labeler and on the feeds had me

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:09.890
working through a lot of questions that it turns out, I

00:05:09.890 --> 00:05:11.540
would need to answer pretty soon.

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:13.870
So things settled for a while.

00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:17.690
But that brings us to last year, 2025.

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:20.720
That's when the delistings happened.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:25.390
A radical group put pressure on payment processors like Visa and Master

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:28.800
Card, who in turn put pressure on game platforms to

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:31.140
delist adult and not-safe-for-work

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:32.180
games from Steam.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:34.350
It happened overnight.

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:35.420
There was no warning.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:39.220
Game developers were waking up to find their content gone, and

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:41.220
the appeals process was scattered at best.

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:45.380
Now, it doesn't matter if you play or care for

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:47.670
adult or not-safe-for-work games.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:48.510
Some people do.

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:50.970
And regardless, those games deserve to exist.

00:05:51.030 --> 00:05:54.340
And the developers that make them deserve to be able to express

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:54.900
their art.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:58.970
But the delistings didn't stop at adult content.

00:05:58.970 --> 00:06:03.770
Marginalized communities like LGBT developers and developers of color

00:06:03.770 --> 00:06:04.960
also got swept up.

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:08.240
Many of these games had nothing to do with adult content,

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:11.140
but they were flagged or pulled because the dragnet

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:13.300
on the delistings was wide.

00:06:13.300 --> 00:06:16.260
And the appeals process, again, was barely functional.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:20.120
A few months later, the same thing happened on itch

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:20.330
.

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:23.490
io, which has long been considered a bastion for indie

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:25.680
games, especially the weird ones.

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:29.580
Developers woke up to find their games gone, revenue gone

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:32.020
, visibility completely wiped.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:35.410
And because none of that data belonged to the developers, there

00:06:35.410 --> 00:06:36.900
was little they could do.

00:06:36.910 --> 00:06:40.450
Now, remember I'm running the labelers, I'm

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:43.110
running the largest game dev feeds on Blue Sky.

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:46.270
I have tens of thousands of developers in this community.

00:06:46.270 --> 00:06:49.060
They're not strangers, they're people that I interact with

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:49.780
regularly.

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:53.140
People I've built a reputation with that have put their trust

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:55.540
in me as a steward of this community.

00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:57.890
So they started reaching out.

00:06:57.890 --> 00:07:00.970
Throughout all of this, they were posting publicly and reaching out

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:02.230
to me privately in DMs.

00:07:02.230 --> 00:07:05.520
And the question was, what can we do to survive this

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:05.680
?

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:09.190
How can we use the atmosphere to make it so that no

00:07:09.190 --> 00:07:13.320
platform and no payment processor has the power to make a developer

00:07:13.450 --> 00:07:14.340
's work disappear?

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:18.850
At first, I said, I don't know, good

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:19.060
luck.

00:07:19.060 --> 00:07:23.660
I already had a lot on my plate, but it sort

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:25.180
of stuck in my head.

00:07:25.180 --> 00:07:27.620
I couldn't really quit thinking about it.

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:29.220
So I did start building.

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:32.980
Before I get into what I actually built, yeah, I

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:34.970
know I do a lot of prefaces.

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:37.860
I'm going to share some things that I picked up along

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:38.260
the way.

00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:42.280
Throughout all this work, I've been trying to convince game

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:45.850
developers to migrate from Twitter to Blue Sky, onto the atmosphere

00:07:45.850 --> 00:07:46.090
.

00:07:46.240 --> 00:07:48.920
And in all of those conversations, I've had to explain

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:51.540
why Blue Sky and the atmosphere mattered.

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:54.350
And I had to do it to people who could not care

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:55.850
less about the protocol.

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:58.740
But if the blueprint that I'm handing you today is going

00:07:58.750 --> 00:08:01.510
to work for other industries, you're going to need to

00:08:01.510 --> 00:08:02.650
do the same thing.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:06.640
So one thing to keep in mind with this is that while

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.480
game devs are people too, they're not average users

00:08:10.480 --> 00:08:10.890
.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:11.940
They're creators.

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:14.860
They often use social media more like a storefront than anything

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:15.300
else.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:17.840
So it's a little bit different than talking to your average

00:08:17.840 --> 00:08:20.260
individual that's just setting up their social media.

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:24.400
So I'm essentially speaking to them like businesses, not individuals

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:24.580
.

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:27.650
With that in mind, here's the framing that I found

00:08:27.650 --> 00:08:28.980
actually clicks.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:33.330
Number one, you choose who stewards your data.

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:35.470
We all know this one, right?

00:08:35.470 --> 00:08:38.160
You get to decide who's responsible for your data.

00:08:38.160 --> 00:08:40.070
If you sign up on Blue Sky, they're the ste

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:40.990
ward of your data.

00:08:40.990 --> 00:08:43.080
If you signed up on Black Sky, you can thank Rudy

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:44.660
and his team for keeping it safe.

00:08:44.670 --> 00:08:46.950
And if you're deeper in the atmosphere, like a lot

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:49.540
of us in this room, maybe your data is on a

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:51.200
raspberry pie in your kitchen.

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:52.050
I don't know.

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.230
The point is, it's your choice.

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:56.870
The control is in your hands, and you can choose a

00:08:56.870 --> 00:08:59.120
new steward later, even if the current one doesn't

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:00.100
want you to leave.

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:02.920
Steam would never.

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:06.260
Number two, your data works everywhere.

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:09.210
If I make a post on Blue Sky, any other app

00:09:09.210 --> 00:09:12.090
that supports those posts, Black Sky, North Sky, Euros

00:09:12.090 --> 00:09:14.180
ky, and a soda, and about a gajillion

00:09:14.180 --> 00:09:16.840
more, can also see that post.

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:20.840
Users on those platforms can like it and engage with it.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:24.260
And if you choose a new steward later, you can

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:27.290
take all of that data with you because it belongs to you

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:29.300
, not to any single platform.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:33.650
And number three, the community is smaller.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:35.380
But this is real.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:40.120
On Twitter, you scream into an algorithm that prioritizes exploitation

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:41.200
over engagement.

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:43.800
On Blue Sky, when you post about your game, the

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:46.440
people who've opted into the game dev feed, they're

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:47.780
there for that content.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:50.290
So they actually see it.

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:55.610
Your screenshot Saturday posts get real engagement from people who genuinely care

00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:57.490
, not bots and drive-by follows.

00:09:57.490 --> 00:10:00.700
For anyone trying to build an audience, whether that's game

00:10:00.700 --> 00:10:04.280
devs, musicians, educators, whoever, a smaller community

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:08.440
paying attention is worth far more than a massive one that isn

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:08.840
't.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:09.890
So that's it.

00:10:09.890 --> 00:10:12.430
That's what's been working for me.

00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:15.670
You own your data, it works everywhere, and the people

00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:16.970
here are actually engaged.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:19.860
That's the spiel that's been working really well for

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:22.700
bringing these folks over to the atmosphere.

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:26.420
So I'd encourage all of you to steal it, because

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:28.710
you'll need it when the people in your industry start asking

00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:29.690
why they should care.

00:10:29.690 --> 00:10:33.140
Okay, so back to the building.

00:10:33.140 --> 00:10:36.760
The community was asking for help, and I had an idea

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:37.860
of how to give it.

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:41.560
The first question I had to answer was, what does video

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:44.480
game data look like on the atmosphere?

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:48.160
Right now, every platform has its own answer.

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:51.690
Steam has its own data format, Epic has its own,

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:55.060
and then there's IGDB, which is worth pausing

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:55.300
on.

00:10:55.310 --> 00:10:59.070
Because IGDB is the de facto game database for most of

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:00.340
the industry.

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:03.350
Discord pulls game data from IGDB.

00:11:03.950 --> 00:11:07.780
So does Xbox, so does Epic, GOG, Unity

00:11:07.790 --> 00:11:10.980
, dozens of major companies depend on it.

00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:16.840
And it's owned by Twitch, which is owned by Amazon

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:17.220
.

00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:21.940
Fun fact, Amazon also owns IMDB.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:28.200
One company controls the authoritative databases for film, television,

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:29.220
and games.

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:34.340
Every one of the platforms I mentioned earlier is building on data

00:11:34.350 --> 00:11:38.050
owned by a single corporation, and the developers whose games are

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:40.900
in the IGDB, they're guests.

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:45.370
They can submit corrections, but they don't own anything.

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:49.070
In my conversations with game developers, I found a lot of

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:52.200
them didn't even know that their games were on the platform

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:54.110
, and they certainly didn't know that they could edit it

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:54.260
.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:58.580
So that's a supply chain risk for an entire industry.

00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:03.760
And for me, sitting there with a community, asking what

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:07.690
can we do, it felt pretty obvious where to start.

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:13.900
Step one was defining a shared language for games on the atmosphere

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:14.110
.

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:18.960
The game lexicons cover everything about a game that you

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:22.100
'd want in any application on the network.

00:12:22.100 --> 00:12:25.860
The game itself, title, descriptions, genres, platforms,

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:29.010
release dates, screenshots, it's offshoots, expans

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:31.630
ions, downloadable content, updates, mods, and then

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:33.280
of course the data around it as well.

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:37.000
So achievements, high scores, reviews, and credits for contributors

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:37.220
.

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:42.380
But because these are lexicons on the protocol, they

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:44.240
're not locked to any single application.

00:12:44.240 --> 00:12:47.210
The developer publishes their game data once to their own PD

00:12:47.210 --> 00:12:50.800
S, and any application on the network that understands the le

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:53.730
xicons can display it, search it, reference it.

00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:57.700
Right now, a game developer updating their game's description has

00:12:57.700 --> 00:12:59.360
to do it on Steam, Epic, GOG, Hum

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:01.280
ble, Itch, IGDB, their own website,

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:03.300
their press kit, their publisher's website.

00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:07.670
With the atmosphere, update it once, it propagates everywhere

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:08.020
.

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:09.700
Well, kinda.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:13.640
We have to be honest about our expectations for adoption, right

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:13.830
?

00:13:13.830 --> 00:13:17.430
Those other platforms aren't going to start pulling from the atmosphere

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:20.200
tomorrow just because the data is there.

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:23.350
We build the foundation, though, because we have to start

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:24.250
somewhere.

00:13:24.250 --> 00:13:27.510
So we build the foundation, we prove the value, and

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:30.600
then over time, we either convince platforms to adopt it,

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:33.630
or we build something so compelling that they don't really have

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:34.340
a choice.

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:35.860
That's the long game.

00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:40.740
Now, lexicons by themselves are just definitions.

00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:44.670
You still need something to make them work on the network.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:46.650
Blue Sky calls it an app view.

00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:49.650
Others call it an app server, or an API, or

00:13:49.670 --> 00:13:50.810
a flibbity gibbet.

00:13:50.810 --> 00:13:52.230
There's a lot of things.

00:13:52.230 --> 00:13:56.260
The proper name and description of an app view are hotly

00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:56.980
contested.

00:13:56.980 --> 00:13:59.680
But really, it's just the layer that sits between the

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:02.020
data on the network and the people trying to use it.

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:05.540
If lexicons are the shared language, the app views

00:14:05.550 --> 00:14:07.740
are the applications that speak it.

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:12.220
Traditionally, building an app view means writing custom software from

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:14.100
scratch for your specific use case.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:16.810
You have to handle indexing records from the network.

00:14:16.810 --> 00:14:19.770
You have to implement queries and procedure XRPCs.

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:21.880
You have to know what XRPCs are.

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:25.750
You probably need to handle authentication, and you'll likely need

00:14:25.760 --> 00:14:28.420
additional infrastructure, databases, search indexes.

00:14:28.430 --> 00:14:30.850
That's a significant amount of work, and it's a

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:34.400
real barrier for anyone who wants to build on the atmosphere.

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:36.380
So, I built HappyView.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:39.640
HappyView is a lexicon-driven app view builder

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:40.020
.

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:43.470
You upload your lexicons, it dynamically generates XR

00:14:43.470 --> 00:14:47.050
PCs for querying and writing data, watches the network

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:49.980
for new records in your lexicon collections, it index

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:52.240
es them, and it proxies rights back to users

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:53.850
' PDSs.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:56.440
You define the schema, you upload it, you have a

00:14:56.440 --> 00:14:57.220
working app view.

00:14:57.220 --> 00:15:00.760
Auth included, out of the box, totally open source,

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:02.900
but HappyView isn't specific to games.

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:03.930
It's generic.

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:06.420
It's open source infrastructure, so you can use it for

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:09.140
whatever industry you're currently looking at.

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:12.520
The game lexicons are the first production use case built

00:15:12.530 --> 00:15:14.810
on HappyView, but I'm hoping they will not be

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:15.520
the last.

00:15:15.550 --> 00:15:20.820
Now, I used HappyView and the games lexicons

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:23.460
to create the Pinteract app view.

00:15:23.460 --> 00:15:27.580
Some of you all may know it by its sort of infamous

00:15:27.580 --> 00:15:29.770
handle, games.

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:30.610
games.

00:15:30.610 --> 00:15:32.020
games.

00:15:32.030 --> 00:15:32.150
games.

00:15:32.150 --> 00:15:32.230
games.

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:34.620
And of course, that means that the NSID for the

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:36.640
game lexicon is games.

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:37.290
games.

00:15:37.410 --> 00:15:38.190
games.

00:15:38.190 --> 00:15:39.060
games.

00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:40.330
game.

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:41.700
You're welcome.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:47.000
Shout out to Ted Han, by the way, for appoint

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.620
ing me at that domain and coming up with the much simpler

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:52.820
name I mentioned just a minute ago, the Pinteract

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:53.050
.

00:15:53.050 --> 00:15:56.690
The Pinteract currently holds data for more than 350,

00:15:56.690 --> 00:15:58.820
000 games across all platforms.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:01.220
You can think of the Pinteract as the alternative to

00:16:01.220 --> 00:16:03.380
the IGDB API.

00:16:03.390 --> 00:16:06.290
It's the open, decentralized version of the game data layer

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:08.570
that the whole industry has been building on.

00:16:08.570 --> 00:16:11.130
And it's currently live and open, so feel free to

00:16:11.130 --> 00:16:13.540
go play with it after I'm done.

00:16:13.540 --> 00:16:16.110
I'll be holding links to the end because I know you

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:18.340
rascals better than to restrain yourselves from a new

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:18.580
toy.

00:16:18.630 --> 00:16:22.530
Now that the data layer was in place, I needed a

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:26.860
way for everyday users, both gamers and developers, to access

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:27.570
that data.

00:16:27.570 --> 00:16:29.700
So that's where Cartridge comes in.

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:34.030
Cartridge is the first application built on the Pinteract

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:34.290
.

00:16:34.290 --> 00:16:38.030
It's a games database, sure, an alternative to IG

00:16:38.030 --> 00:16:41.020
DB itself, but it's also a games discovery platform for

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.670
players, where I'm building features to make it easier for

00:16:43.750 --> 00:16:45.940
gamers to find the games that they love.

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:48.770
But more importantly, and sort of back to the mission,

00:16:48.770 --> 00:16:51.740
it's where developers can go to take control of their game

00:16:51.740 --> 00:16:52.290
's data.

00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:55.940
Game developers aren't going to interact with raw lexicons

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:58.430
and app views and XRPCs, and they shouldn

00:16:58.430 --> 00:16:59.210
't have to.

00:16:59.210 --> 00:17:03.140
They're building games, not infrastructure for the atmosphere.

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:06.180
When a developer signs in, they get a dashboard, from

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:10.030
there they can create game records, update descriptions, upload screenshots

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:13.300
, manage credits, all the stuff that they're currently doing

00:17:13.310 --> 00:17:15.690
across 10 different platforms.

00:17:15.690 --> 00:17:19.380
Except now they're doing it once on their terms, and

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:21.620
the data lives in their PDS.

00:17:21.620 --> 00:17:24.660
Okay, that actually means they're doing it 11 times now

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:27.060
, but we talked about this long game.

00:17:28.670 --> 00:17:33.210
Now, IGDB itself has around 350,000 games.

00:17:33.370 --> 00:17:35.930
That may sound familiar, because that's about how many games

00:17:35.930 --> 00:17:37.160
we have on cartridge.

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:40.370
Actually, that's exactly the same number, because IGDB

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:43.940
is the original source of all the data that is currently in

00:17:43.940 --> 00:17:45.040
the Pinteract.

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:46.500
And yes, I did check.

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:48.900
IGDB's API allows me to do that.

00:17:48.910 --> 00:17:52.960
But it gets better over time, as developers claim and take

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:54.500
ownership of their games.

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:57.960
They enrich the data, and we can build a rich graph

00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:02.010
of the data between games and other things on the network,

00:18:02.010 --> 00:18:03.870
like blue sky posts, pop feed.

00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:08.170
social reviews, leaflet and pocket articles referencing games.

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:12.020
And there are technical advantages, real technical advantages to using the

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:13.700
Pinteract app view over IGDB.

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.980
There's no Twitch credentials necessary for one thing.

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:20.020
You get unauthenticated API access, we have semantic

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:23.680
search instead of plain text matching, and we have discovery feeds

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:25.060
that IGDB simply doesn't offer.

00:18:25.060 --> 00:18:28.090
But the important part isn't the feature comparison.

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:30.900
It's what happens when a developer actually claims their game.

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:37.310
They verify ownership, they claim the record, and they migrate

00:18:37.340 --> 00:18:38.090
it to their PDS.

00:18:38.100 --> 00:18:40.660
Now it's theirs, fully.

00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:43.400
Their data is managed by the steward of their choice rather

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:44.970
than the devil, I mean Amazon.

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:49.970
If cartridge disappears tomorrow, their game data would still be on

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:53.800
the network in their PDS accessible to any application that speaks

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:54.700
to the lexicons.

00:18:54.700 --> 00:18:58.410
That right there, that's what data sovereignty means, right

00:18:58.410 --> 00:18:58.740
?

00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:01.050
It's not just a buzzword, it's a technical

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:01.690
reality.

00:19:01.710 --> 00:19:02.980
We're doing it on the atmosphere.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:07.890
Now cartridge isn't officially launched.

00:19:07.890 --> 00:19:10.560
I can't tell you about tremendous user growth or anything.

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:13.000
There's no press releases, no big announcements, and I

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.740
still have some work to finish before I'm comfortable really opening

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:17.360
the floodgates on the application.

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:20.140
So the social proof of all this may feel a little bit

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:23.210
flimsy, but what's happened during development is what

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:25.460
really tells me that I've been on the right track.

00:19:25.460 --> 00:19:29.600
When I started sharing my work on the Pinteract publicly

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:33.240
, developers started responding with use cases I hadn't considered.

00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:36.820
Luca from the Northsky team brought up managing a game's

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:39.260
credits and updating them regularly.

