HappyView, and Cartridge.

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:43.720
Now, let's talk a little bit about what other atmosphere

00:22:43.730 --> 00:22:46.010
builders can hopefully take away from it.

00:22:46.100 --> 00:22:50.010
I took a community that I was already a part of.

00:22:50.010 --> 00:22:53.160
I found the data that causes the most pain for my community

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:56.770
, which in my case was games scattered across platforms that developers

00:22:56.770 --> 00:22:59.640
don't control, and I built tools and infrastructure that let

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:00.480
them own it.

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:02.810
That's not unique to games, though.

00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:04.860
It's a pattern, and once you see it, it

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:06.810
's a little difficult to unsee.

00:23:06.810 --> 00:23:08.490
Take music, for example.

00:23:08.490 --> 00:23:11.500
An artist releases a track, and now they're managing metadata

00:23:11.500 --> 00:23:14.710
across Spotify, Apple Music, Bandcamp, SoundCloud,

00:23:14.790 --> 00:23:15.810
YouTube, Tidal.

00:23:15.810 --> 00:23:19.440
Every platform has its own dashboard, its own format, and

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:20.510
its own rules.

00:23:20.510 --> 00:23:24.600
An artist gets dropped, or a distributor folds, and suddenly

00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:26.550
the musician's catalog is in limbo.

00:23:26.550 --> 00:23:29.730
Their fans can't find their music, their revenue disappears.

00:23:29.730 --> 00:23:32.030
It's the same pattern, but it's a different industry

