00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:28.580
domain knowledge.

00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:29.750
So that's it.

00:25:29.750 --> 00:25:32.900
You can do this for music, for education, you can

00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:35.310
do it for healthcare records, for legal documents, for anything

00:25:35.310 --> 00:25:38.580
where centralization is failing the people who create the data.

00:25:38.580 --> 00:25:39.810
This is one pattern.

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:43.300
It's not the only centralization problem out there, but

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:46.770
your domain might have a slightly different one, locked up credentials

00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.730
, gated access, licensing nightmares.

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:52.240
The pattern might look slightly different, but the tooling that I

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:56.260
've shown you today, it should be generic enough to handle

00:25:56.260 --> 00:25:57.580
pretty much all of them.

00:25:57.580 --> 00:26:00.660
The hardest part is figuring out what data in your domain actually

00:26:00.670 --> 00:26:04.150
needs to be decentralized, and then designing lexicons that

00:26:04.150 --> 00:26:05.770
accurately represent it.

00:26:05.770 --> 00:26:09.170
That's domain expertise, not protocol expertise, and that's

00:26:09.170 --> 00:26:12.310
why it really has to come from people who know their industries

00:26:12.310 --> 00:26:15.610
, not from people outside guessing at what a community needs.

00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:17.860
One more thing.

00:26:17.860 --> 00:26:21.790
I've been talking about the protocol a lot because y'

00:26:21.790 --> 00:26:24.660
all are the people building on it, right?

00:26:24.660 --> 00:26:27.850
But when I'm talking to a game developer about cartridge or

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:30.170
about blue sky, none of this comes up.

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:32.980
They don't know what an app view is.

00:26:32.980 --> 00:26:35.450
Like I said earlier, they don't care about XR

00:26:35.450 --> 00:26:35.830
PCs.

00:26:35.830 --> 00:26:39.680
They just want to manage their game data and not get screwed

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:41.430
by big corporations.

00:26:41.430 --> 00:26:45.490
The protocol is invisible in the product and in the conversations.

00:26:45.550 --> 00:26:47.570
That's not an accident.

00:26:47.570 --> 00:26:49.270
That's the whole point.

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:53.860
Everything I've built treats at protocol as an implementation detail,

00:26:53.860 --> 00:26:55.330
not the selling point.

00:26:55.330 --> 00:26:58.410
It's not why a game developer would use cartridge.

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:00.660
They'd use it because it solves their problems.

00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:03.120
The protocol is just how it works under the hood.

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:06.590
So when you go to build for your industry, that's

00:27:06.590 --> 00:27:09.710
the mindset that's going to get people to use what you

00:27:09.850 --> 00:27:10.420
make.

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:13.180
Don't sell the protocol, solve the problem.

00:27:13.180 --> 00:27:16.330
The protocol is what makes your solution possible, but it's

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:17.380
never the pitch.

00:27:17.380 --> 00:27:18.340
Thank you.

00:27:27.790 --> 00:27:29.960
That was fantastic, Tracy.

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:34.020
I hope a bunch of people are lighting up their scrapers

00:27:34.020 --> 00:27:37.300
and attacking so many other industries.

00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:41.370
The fire safety talk was one that would pair really nicely with

00:27:41.370 --> 00:27:44.090
yours because they have the same pain.

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:45.160
Thank you.

00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:46.180
Awesome.

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:46.180
Yep.
